        description: "Northeastern University Charlotte's Accelerated Bachelor of Science in Nursing (ABSN) program is designed to address North Carolina's critical nursing shortage by providing an accelerated pathway for career changers and second-degree students to earn a BSN in as few as 16 months. The program is unique in North Carolina, accepting students with either a non-nursing bachelor's degree or at least 62 college credits. Our state-of-the-art clinical training facilities include four advanced simulation rooms and a 10-bed skills lab that serve as safe, contextual learning environments where students integrate theory with practice while making real-time clinical decisions. The simulation rooms feature observation and control capabilities, allowing faculty to create realistic clinical scenarios with adjustable vitals and real-time patient interactions, including specialized high-fidelity manikins like \"simulation mom\" (capable of full birth delivery and obstetric emergencies) and \"simulation man\" (designed for elder care scenarios with challenging vascular access). These manikins can talk, communicate, able to swallow, and reproduce biological functions to realistically portray high-risk scenarios such as cardiac arrest or severe hemorrhaging, followed by reflective debriefing sessions where faculty provide feedback in a non-graded environment that encourages honest self-assessment. The program employs a robust part-time faculty network drawn primarily from our local hospital partners—including Atrium Health, CaroMont Health and Novant Health—creating a direct pipeline from education to employment while ensuring students learn from practicing clinicians. Our graduates excel in clinical practice and have also demonstrated success in entrepreneurship and innovation, extending nursing's impact beyond traditional clinical settings.",
        problem_opportunity: "North Carolina faces a severe nursing shortage that threatens healthcare access and quality across the state, with 13% of the state’s registered nurse positions currently unfilled. The ABSN program addresses this crisis by creating an accelerated, accessible pathway for individuals with existing college education to transition into nursing careers quickly and affordably. Traditional BSN programs require 2 years of nursing and often exclude qualified candidates due to limited faculty and clinical sites who already hold degrees or significant college credits in other fields. Our 16-month accelerated model recognizes and builds upon students' prior learning, reducing time to workforce entry while maintaining rigorous clinical preparation. By employing practicing nurses from our hospital partners as adjunct faculty, we ensure students learn current best practices while building relationships that facilitate employment transitions. Our advanced simulation facilities address the challenge of clinical preparedness by providing safe, controlled environments where students can practice complex scenarios—from high-risk obstetric emergencies to geriatric care—before encountering them with real patients.",
