        description: "EESC3000 is a 4-credit asynchronous course designed to help STEM students develop ethical reasoning skills, professional identity, and reflective practice. Since Fall 2023, I have co-led a comprehensive redesign of the course, initially in collaboration with Cheryl Arruda, transforming it into a high-impact, interdisciplinary experience that integrates ethical theory with real-world application. The course fulfills the NUPath Ethical Reasoning requirement and has attracted students from across disciplines, expanding its reach beyond the College of Science. It is offered in both full-semester and accelerated formats, with consistent student engagement and exceptional evaluation scores.",
        problem_opportunity: "EESC3000 supports Northeastern’s mission of experiential, interdisciplinary, and ethical education by: - Bridging academic learning with co-op experiences. - Promoting DEI through modules on bias, mentorship, and epistemic pushback. - Encouraging professional development and leadership in STEM fields. - Providing a scalable model for asynchronous, high-impact ethics instruction.  Leadership and Expansion  As Associate Director of Co-op, I have: - Created onboarding materials and mentorship structures for new instructors. - Led adaptation of the course for accelerated formats. - Developed a pipeline for instructor training through Canvas access and biweekly meetings. - Invested 10–15 hours per week outside of normal working hours to refine content, record lectures, and provide feedback.  This course exemplifies how co-op faculty can lead transformative educational initiatives that align with Northeastern’s strategic priorities and enhance student learning across disciplines.  As part of the initial redesign, we expanded the content in the original course as previously taught to allow for a more in depth analysis of each of the three ethical theories presented, and we used a podcast or documentary as a case study for each theory. We intentionally tied in professional goal setting through each week’s assignments, including questions such as “ How will you apply your knowledge of this case to your future academic or professional career?”  I then built out an instructor recruitement and onboarding process, integrated with regular support in advance of and throughout the semester, that has led to three additional instructors joining the pipeline and teaching the course.",
        challenges: "Variation in student writing abilities and AI use in asnychronous course format",
        impact: "Student impact statements demonstrate strong engagement with the material as well as with peers and instructors in the asynchronous format. Examples include: “This was probably my favorite class at Northeastern. The assignments were meaningful, the feedback was thoughtful, and I felt like I was learning something I could carry into my future career.” “This course allowed me to explore my career interests and incorporate them with ethical concepts… I HIGHLY recommend this course for anyone new to science ethics.” \"Learning about philosophical and ethical dilemmas has never been my favorite topic in school. I would always skim through readings and answer questions at the bare minimum. At the beginning of the summer, I started this class expecting that I would do the same––glance over the readings and skip through the videos just enough to complete the assignments. However, I was very quickly proven wrong. The first module that really changed my outlook was Module 3 – Informed Consent and Henrietta Lacks. I was so fascinated by the case and ethical dilemma behind it, that I didn’t just stop at the podcast; I went and bought The Immortal Life of Henrietta Lacks on my Kindle. After that, the cases became more and more interesting (MegaSyn AI technology - so cool!) and I found myself doing the complete opposite of what I used to. Instead of barely looking over the material, I was researching more about it on my own.  I think that one of the biggest contributors to this was the discussion post format. I would end my own post with lots of ideas, questions, comments, and concerns. Reading my classmates’ posts showed me that everybody had even more ideas that I hadn’t explored. Sometimes their posts answered my questions, and sometimes they made me come up with even more. Regardless, I loved being in a setting where I could consider so many perspectives. Many of us are going into similar fields of work, and it is especially interesting to see so many points of views that relate to a similar end goal. \" \"I liked the \"no right answer aspect\" of this course. I felt like no matter what I said, I had a valid point and was able to express that. I think that I would love to continue having these conversations going forward in a similar way.\"",
