        target_audience: "Undergraduate students;Faculty;Staff;Industry partners;",
        partners: "Chancellor’s Office / Vice Chancellor for Experiential Education Co-op offices across Northeastern colleges UC Irvine research team (College-to-Career Measurement Project) External assessment providers  Employer advisory partners participating in structured skills feedback and co-educator roles.",
        evaluation_methods: "Surveys/feedback forms;Performance metrics;Comparative studies;Focus groups/interviews;Usage analytics;Academic outcomes;",
        data_results: "Existing research include research reports from the first stage of our experiential learning research, which shows extremely high co-op satisfaction (42% “extremely,” 39% “very” satisfied) and strong employment outcomes, but also reveals that co-op quality—especially task complexity, perceived learning, and supervision quality—drives satisfaction and early labor-market success. High-skill and autonomous tasks are associated with the highest satisfaction, and functional specialization across co-ops is strongly related to avoiding underemployment and accessing higher-status occupations. These findings are directly informing the choice of competencies, instruments, and intervention points in the real-time assessment system.",
