        challenges: "One challenge has been maintaining consistent engagement from mentees throughout the entire term. Some mentor-mentee pairs start strong but lose momentum after the first few weeks, especially during busy periods like midterms and finals. We've also found that not all pairings click right away, and it can be difficult for students to communicate when a match isn't working for them. In terms of coordination, the program requires a high level of time, commitment, and personalized engagement with all mentors, as well as thoughtful matching and facilitation.",
        impact: "Many Toronto students have been involved in the program as either mentees or mentors over the last 4 years. The most significant impact has been the sense of belonging and community that participants report having developed through the program. Mentees consistently share that having someone who \"gets it\" and can relate to their concerns has made them feel less alone and more confident navigating campus/university life. Many mention that their mentor helped them navigate and discover resources or opportunities they would never have found on their own.   For mentors, we have seen growth in leadership capabilities and self-awareness. Mentors often tell us that being a mentor has improved their own time management, leadership, problem-solving, and communication skills.   We are also seeing mentors and mentees continuing to connect with one another after the term ends, having made new friends, with mentees already expressing interest in becoming mentors themselves. This creates a positive cycle where students who were once supported are now eager to give back, building a stronger and more connected campus community overall.",
