        additional_info: "Having a student led event helps showcase the great work and achievements a student club or organization can achieve. Partnering the student group with advisors and faculty allows for a collaborative event with outreach and support from the college to plan and market the event. Below I am adding the additional information from the student leader for the 2025 Health Fair, Sydney Snyder:   Every April, our chapter of Phi Delta Chi holds elections for all positions, including the Bouvé Health Fair head. Immediately after the elections, the planning begins! It starts slowly by reaching out to the faculty coordinators and starting to think about the previous years' events in the sense of what you want to do the same and what you want to change. After that comes the endless emails to potential sponsors. These start early and ultimately are the most time-consuming and one of the most important tasks to do. To make the event successful, we need to have products that help advertise and make the event more enticing. By starting early and sending individualized emails, we are usually able to get a substantial amount of donations from extremely generous companies.   Then the bulk of the planning kicks in when it is time to work with Northeastern Facilities to book the spaces for the event. This part takes a lot of communication with different offices at Northeastern to manage a lot of logistical efforts to make the event take place.   Also, around this time, we start to design the poster for the year; this is done in collaboration with our media E-board member, as well as our faculty advisors and the Bouvé marketing head. We work hard on the design to make it something that grasps people's attention; it plays a key role in the success of the event.   At the end of the summer, we reach out to student organizations and other health offices at NU and faculty-run organizations in hopes of getting presenters. The more presenters we are able to have, the better the experience. I believe we get a lot of foot traffic due to people needing vaccines, but these presenters really make the event lively, fun, and engaging to learn about pressing health topics and safety for undergraduate students, graduate students, faculty, and staff alike.   Lastly, organizing volunteers to staff the event on the day of, there is a lot of scrambling and setup that could certainly not be managed by one person. There are amazing volunteers from Phi Delta Chi as well as other organizations that help the fair go smoothly!  There is so much more that goes on behind the scenes, as well as a huge community of people who help plan and organize this event. Although our professional organization has its lead organizer, this event could not be pulled off alone."
