        description: "A lab-only course (4 SH) that promotes the development of key scientific skills and competencies, while drawing on the research expertise of Biology faculty.  Students collaborate to design, implement, and present research that leverages current scientific models. Students can continue their research projects beyond the semester, under the supervision of their project lab teaching professor, using the new Wet Lab Makerspace in EXP.  The skills incorporated in this course were determined in consultation with our leading co-op employers to ensure that this course effectively prepared students for their co-op projects.       The makerspace has advanced equipment that the teaching Biology labs do not have. Students can use the equipment in the space for their project and/or continue the project after the semester is over. For example, the makerspace has equipment such as a flow cytometer and a plate reader. The makerspace staff trains the students how to use the equipment which allows the students to do the work themselves and advance their skills. Overall, having access to this facility and its equipment during or after the semester, allows the students to design projects that are more creative and tackle more complex research questions. One student project from the class resulted in a scientific publication in the microPublication Biology journal.",
        problem_opportunity: "Biology Project Lab is an open inquiry-based class. Students have access to a set of materials and organisms, and after reviewing the literature they design and execute their own projects aft. But they do not know what the outcome will be and neither does their professor. For most students, this is the first time they get to design and execute their own independent research project. Overall, open-inquiry lab based classes are rare because they can be quite challenging to run and scale up to be taken by hundreds of students each year. In the process, students improve their research skills tremendously and gain more independence with the scientific research which they can leverage in their future research positions in academia or industry.  The Makerspace allows students access to instruments that they would not normally get to use in the teaching labs. It also gives them access to additional training.   The course and access to the Makerspace allows them the opportunity to continue, expand and improve the work done during the semester, under the supervision of their Project lab professor, and this work may result in a scientific publication.",
        challenges: "Challenges related to the class - scaling it up to accommodate close to 500 students a year. Each section of the class is capped at 16 students because each group is working on their unique project needing close supervision and support by their professor.  Makerspace - it is an extra step for students to get trained and they may not always take that extra step. However, the training at the Makerspace is very well organized and managed. It is also relatively fast as long as the students start the planning early and manage to align their training with their project’s schedule.   They are equipped with complex and sophisticated instruments but sometimes students need the basic ones as well.",
